Viviane Clay: And again, I'll start
with the shoutouts to the community.

And… yeah, this month was pretty busy for
me, and then took some PTO, so I actually

haven't had a time to check this course
the past two weeks, and so hopefully

I'm not misrepresenting anything,
missing stuff, but if I did, then I'll
mention those people in the next month.

But yeah, we've had some
more PRs from Agent Rev, who…

finalize the simulator protocol cleanup,
which I don't know if you remember, but

during our Brighton retreat, Tristan and
Will prototyped this on a separate fork of

Monty, and then there was this issue here
that the protocol should be reduced, and

Tristan outlined a bunch of changes
that would need to be made for that,

and basically said, yeah, this is a
lot of work, so don't feel like you

have to sign up for all of it, but
Agent Drive did sign up for all of it.
Jeff: Woohoo!
Viviane Clay: And, completed it.
Jeff: Wow.
Viviane Clay: Yeah.

this was the last PR that was merged
a couple… last week, and yeah, I

basically asked what's… what's next
on the… on the map, and Tristan

pointed out another related part that
could be… could be done next, and
there's already an open PR with that.

So… Thanks a lot, for
all these great changes.
And for, yeah, still being interested.

And yeah, just for those who enjoy
these kind of things, like me, a
short video of checking off this item.
From the
roadmap.
There we go.
Very satisfying.
Jeff: Is it…
Viviane Clay: Check things off.

And then, yeah, I also had some
more PRs from MeiMe, reducing
MyPi errors, and some refactoring.

And then a lot of PRs from Carver, there
are actually two slides full of PRs,

Basically around addressing rough
linting rules and some fixes and
refactors on various parts of the code.
So thanks a lot for all those.
Jeff: Nice.

Viviane Clay: And then, yeah,
after the community event, and

also a few before, we had several
new introductions on the forum.
So, welcome to Daniel, Timothy, Bryce.

To Ash and Andreas and Sergio,
thanks for joining the forum
and for introducing yourselves.

Really happy to see
that you're interested.
Oh, and more introductions.
a phone from Janius and Avner.

So, yeah, I think it was the month
of new introductions on the forum.

And, yeah, if anyone else is interested,
I think this is a great way to get

started, to just kind of introduce
yourself, your interests, and…

If you're interested in contributing
in any part of the project, or if

you have questions, or a particular
part you find interesting, that's a…

A great way to get some pointers from the
team and from other people on the forum.

And then, yeah, also a
couple of first-time posts.
Here one person sharing interactive
visualizations.

an interesting post around some
ideas for modeling deformations.

It was a problem we discussed in
one of our research meetings about

Deformation from circle to
an egg and back, and how that
could be modeled and learned.
You know, sharing a paper on our forum.

And… Yeah, another interesting, post that
started in an email thread, and then…

Nicely moved over to the forum, so
everyone can follow along about…

solid brain theory and, applying
Monty to text understanding.

Interesting post around
language and the mind.

And… Bryce shared a 6-minute
explainer video condensing some
of our video… longer videos
into playlists.

Another post around learning
categories of objects, and some
thoughts around, attention.

more interesting posts,
some… a post from Agent Rev.
with some ideas around, Monty.

a poster from Rich around predictive
error processing and sensitivity,

and some questions about references
for grid cell papers in response to
one of our videos about grid cells.

Then sharing the project, Zach,
he's building a robot using
Monty as part of his thesis.

And he made a short 2-minute explainer
video for one of his courseworks,
and shared that video on LinkedIn.

It's a really nice high-level
overview of Feldenbrian's theory.

And then, yeah, sharing the project,
there was also Mount Preet, who
wrote a blog post about Monty.

And shared it on LinkedIn, and then
just, generally, sharing our meetup.
Here Danish shared,

picture of him watching Jeff's
presentation from the meetup.
For example.

So yeah, thanks a lot also to anyone
who's sharing the project and, or writing
blog posts or producing videos around it.
It's a really great way to help us.
Spread the word.
